.TH TEETAP 1 "2026" "teetap 0.1.0" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
teetap \- detachable, tee-based local log tap for agents and humans
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B teetap run
[\fB--rotate\fR|\fB--truncate\fR|\fB--split\fR]
.I name
\fB--\fR
.I command
[\fIargs\fR...]
.br
.I producer
| \fBteetap pipe\fR
.I name
.br
.B teetap pm2 link
[\fIname-filter\fR...]
.br
.B teetap path
.br
.B teetap status
.br
.B teetap list
.br
.B teetap off
[\fB--force\fR]
.br
.B teetap skill install
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B teetap
captures the output of local processes to one well-known directory per
project, outside the repository, so that coding agents and other observers
can read it with
.BR tail (1)
and
.BR grep (1)
without owning the process. It is runtime-agnostic: it moves bytes and does
not care what produced them.
.PP
Each project (git worktree) gets its own directory under the aggregate root
(default
.IR ~/.local/state/teetap ),
keyed by the toplevel's basename and a hash of its absolute path. Because
captures live outside the repository, branching, committing, and conflict
resolution never interact with them.
.SH COMMANDS
.TP
\fBrun\fR [\fB--rotate\fR|\fB--truncate\fR|\fB--split\fR] \fIname\fR \fB--\fR \fIcommand\fR [\fIargs\fR...]
Run
.I command
with stderr merged into stdout, teeing output to
.IR name .log
in the project directory while passing it through to the terminal. The
wrapped command's exit code is recorded in the session end marker and
propagated as teetap's own exit status. By default output is appended;
.B --rotate
moves the existing log to
.IR name .prev.log
first,
.B --truncate
clobbers it in place, and
.B --split
writes a new
.IR name . session-id .log
per run.
.TP
\fBpipe\fR \fIname\fR
Act as a sink: read stdin, stamp a session start marker, append through
.BR tee (1)
to
.IR name .log
while passing the stream to stdout, and stamp an end marker on EOF. Use it
to tap producers that cannot be wrapped: pipelines, remote tails, container
logs.
.TP
\fBpm2 link\fR [\fIname-filter\fR...]
Symlink PM2's existing log files into the project directory with a
.B pm2-
filename prefix. All log files by default, or only those whose names match
a given filter. Idempotent: re-running adds new files and prunes dead
links. Output is never re-piped or duplicated.
.TP
.B path
Print the project directory for the current working directory. This is the
single authority for the naming convention; scripts and agents should use
it rather than deriving paths themselves.
.TP
.B status
List each source as NAME, TYPE (tee file or link), BYTES, and AGE_S
(seconds since last write). An age near zero means the source is actively
writing.
.TP
.B list
List every tapped project under the aggregate root as PROJECT, PATH
(the source directory recorded when the project was first tapped),
SOURCES, and AGE_S, most recently active first. Use it to find logs for
a project that was tapped from a different working directory.
.TP
\fBoff\fR [\fB--force\fR]
Detach: remove all symlinks unconditionally (targets are untouched) and
delete capture files, except files written within the last 10 seconds,
which are treated as live and skipped with a warning unless
.B --force
is given.
.TP
\fBskill install\fR [\fB--allow-fetch\fR]
Install the agent skill to the skills directory (default
.IR ~/.claude/skills/teetap )
so coding agents know how to find and query the logs. The recommended
onboarding is the skills.sh ecosystem:
.PP
.nf
    npx skills add https://github.com/weefaa/teetap --skill teetap
.fi
.PP
.B teetap skill install
is the no-Node fallback. It is offline by default: it copies the skill
bundled next to the script (repository checkout), or writes the SKILL.md
embedded in the binary itself, version-locked to this release. With
.B --allow-fetch
it downloads the full skill structure (SKILL.md, EXAMPLES.md, any future
files) from this binary's own release tag in a single tarball.
.SH SESSION MARKERS
Every capture session is bracketed in the log file by marker lines:
.PP
.nf
===== teetap session <id> start <time> name=<n> branch=<b> cwd=<c> pid=<p> =====
===== teetap session <id> end <time> name=<n> exit=<code> =====
.fi
.PP
Readers should scope to the text after the last start marker to see only
the current run.
.SH ENVIRONMENT
.TP
.B TEETAP_DIR
Aggregate root. Default:
.IR ~/.local/state/teetap .
.TP
.B TEETAP_PM2_LOGS
PM2 log directory. Default:
.IR ~/.pm2/logs .
.TP
.B TEETAP_SKILLS_DIR
Agent skills directory. Default:
.IR ~/.claude/skills .
.TP
.B TEETAP_REPO
GitHub repository used when fetching the skill standalone. Default:
.IR weefaa/teetap .
.SH EXAMPLES
Tap a dev server (any runtime) and watch it live from another terminal:
.PP
.nf
$ teetap run dev -- npm run dev
$ tail -f "$(teetap path)"/dev.log
.fi
.PP
Tap a stream that cannot be wrapped:
.PP
.nf
$ kubectl logs -f mypod | teetap pipe mypod
.fi
.PP
Query the aggregate like a log store:
.PP
.nf
$ grep -h "<request-id>" "$(teetap path)"/*.log
$ sed -n '/13:18:00/,/13:18:30/p' "$(teetap path)"/dev.log
.fi
.SH FILES
.TP
.I ~/.local/state/teetap/<project>-<hash>/
Per-project log directory: real files from captures, symlinks from sources.
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR tee (1),
.BR tail (1),
.BR grep (1),
.BR sed (1)
